And with the awareness amongst the construction companies that they need to spend on technology to drive greater efficiencies, that\xe2\x80\x99s where there is lots of investment. So, lots of interesting startups on the construction side. On the manufacturing side, now I haven\xe2\x80\x99t seen anything interesting out there, but - and the other dynamic is really just the established companies being relatively conservative in moving to the technology platform.
Unidentified Analyst
Just to kind of think of - talk about the cost side of the equation a little bit, in this past quarter I think we were talking about maybe 1% total expense growth year-over-year, one of the slower rates of growth that we\xe2\x80\x99ve seen from Autodesk in a while. Where were you able to find that increased efficiency? It seems like we are expecting that same level of efficiency going to the next quarter with kind of a similar growth rate attached? And how do you think about some of those efficiencies that you\xe2\x80\x99ve been able to - that you started to kind of ring out in context of that mid-single-digit growth rate that we talked about for in expenses through 2020?
Carl Bass
Yeah. I mean, so what I would say is, we came in at about 1%, and we said same thing about Q4, we said through FY17, 1% to 2% growth. Part of where we\xe2\x80\x99ve talked about efficiencies for a number of years is that for right now we\xe2\x80\x99ve been running kind of double models, so we have two kinds of development, a desktop model and a cloud model. We have sales and marketing that\xe2\x80\x99s both kind of new model and old model and add some of the old models you start deprecating them and as they diminish in terms of the investment they need, those then start becoming lower cost.
So there is always the straight off between really two things. How much you want to invest in the future and how much risk you want to put on it. We think the business model is really compelling when you look out to the future. If you look out three years and you are through the transition, people have moved to the cloud, don\xe2\x80\x99t want to jeopardize, we want to invest, but on the other hand, one of the things we certainly heard from our large long term shareholders is during this period in which the transition goes on, can\xe2\x80\x99t you be more careful on cost. So starting early in the year we started saying, yeah, we got places on the margin that we could be more conservative.
And then there are some trends in the business that drive cost out of the system that it\xe2\x80\x99s just natural and so we certainly did some of that. And then we just did the usual kind of [indiscernible] really important and much critical and where can you take on a little more risk without diminishing the reward. And so we did the usual work in running the business. And so what we\xe2\x80\x99ve said for now is, you will see it these two quarters; you will see it for four quarters next year. I would imagine it continues beyond, but we will talk about that as we make our way through the transition.
